  "doc_id": "50910",
  "text": "Elucidating the physiological function of Syt IV requires a native preparation that expresses substantial levels of this protein. Syt IV is relatively scarce in the brain [CITATION_1] , but we found high levels in posterior pituitary nerve terminals. In experiments with this neuropeptidesecreting structure in wild-type and Syt IV knockout mice, we localized Syt IV to dense-core vesicles (DCVs) and microvesicles and found that Syt IV altered Ca 2+ -triggered exocytosis of both. Furthermore, Syt IV altered fusion pores and regulated the kinetics of rapid compensatory endocytosis. Thus, Syt IV participates in several distinct secretory functions in nerve terminals, establishing Syt IV as an important regulator of release from nerve terminals.",
